<p>Apparently, yes it does. I can't find any explanation of the mechanic behind this and would be very interested to find it.</p>
<p>Whatever the case, to the best of my knowledge, no naturally occuring radioactive ore glows. Normally radioluminescence requires the addition of a phosphor or similar agent that is excited by the radiation and later drops down to a lower energy state, releasing visible light in the process. Radium appears to be the exception, but I suspect its luminescence is due to a chemical process (possibly part of the oxidation?), not a radioactive one: radioactive decay just isn't visible.</p>

